LAST UPDATES

Scholarships for Bavarian and Israeli Early Career Researchers

The Bavarian Research Alliance offers early career researchers (PhD students and higher) from Bavaria and Israel who work in the fields of artificial intelligence, social sciences and/or humanities a one-month scholarship to stay abroad at a Bavarian/Israeli research institute. The program aims to provide new opportunities for participants to further develop their academic careers and strengthen their international networks and at the same time to strengthen Bavarian-Israeli scientific relations.

Read more here

Data4ML awarded ERC grant

Prof. Dr. Alexander Fraser, working at the Center for Information and Language Processing and as a Principal Investigator at the Munich Center for Machine Learning (MCML), has received a Proof of Concept Grant from the ERC for his project "Data4ML". The project will produce an open-source prototype of a machine translation systems for languages without large corpora of text to train on. This might help preserve some of the 7000 languages spoken on earth.

Read more here

Data Science for Social Good

The Data Science for Social Good (DSSG) fellowship program is coming to Munich with a two-month program that runs from August 1 to September 29, 2023. The program aims to bring together interdisciplinary teams with diverse backgrounds and skillsets to work on meaningful projects that enhance the use of data science and AI for social good. The fellowships are full-time and come with a scholarship, as well as hands-on project work, support from technical mentors and project managers, educational lectures, social events and group outings. The deadline for applications is February 15, 2023, and the program is open to recent graduates, PhD students, master students, or bachelor students towards the end of their degree from diverse backgrounds.

Read more here

LMU AI Researchers in the News

Prof. Dr. Albrecht Schmidt, Head of the Human-Centered Ubiquitous Media Group, has been interviewed by n-tv.de about ChatGPT and how it could come to influence society. Prof. Dr. Gitta Kutyniok, Bavarian AI Chair for Mathematical Foundations of AI, has been interviewed by ZDF heute about the role of immigration in AI research.

 

Funding Programs at MCML

The Munich Center for Machine Learning (MCML) is offering funding programs for early-career researchers in the field of Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning, including PhD positions, Junior Research Group Leaders, and more. Junior researchers have the opportunity to lead their own research groups, supervise a team of PhD students, and collaborate with leading experts in the field with access to state-of-the-art resources and support. PhD positions offer full stipend support and a dynamic international research environment. Candidates should have a strong background in AI/ML related fields and a PhD or equivalent degree for Junior Research Group Leaders, and an excellent master's degree in computer science, mathematics, or related field for PhD applicants. The application deadline for both programs is February 28th, 2023.

Read more here
UPCOMING EVENTS

AI.BAY 2023

Join the Bavarian State Minister of Science, Markus Blume, the Minister for Digital Affairs, Judith Gerlach, and the Minister of Economic Affairs, Hubert Aiwanger, in exploring the latest advances and the potential of artificial intelligence at AI.BAY 2023 - Bavarian International Conference on AI. The two-day conference, taking place on 23rd and 24th February 2023 hybrid online and at the Deutsches Museum, will provide a platform for leading experts from the Bavarian AI Network and international guests to discuss and present the future of AI.

Register and read more here

Visualizing (Bio-)Medicine with Artificial Intelligence

The "Next Generation AI" series by the CAS is hosting its final event for this semester titled "Visualizing (Bio-)Medicine with Artificial Intelligence," a podium discussion featuring Prof. Dr. Laura Busse of LMU in System Neurobiology, Prof. Dr. Frederick Klauschen, Director of the Pathological Institute of LMU, and Prof. Dr. Björn Menze of the University of Zurich in Biomedical Image Analysis and Machine Learning. The discussion will be moderated by Prof. Dr. Michael Ingrisch and Prof. Dr. Björn Ommer from LMU. The event will take place on February 6th, 2023 at 7:00 pm.

Register and read more here

Munich AI Lecture with Prof. Dr. Peter Flach

The Munich AI Lectures series continues with a talk by Prof. Dr. Peter Flach, Professor of Artificial Intelligence at the University of Bristol. He is an internationally leading scholar in the evaluation and improvement of machine learning models using ROC analysis and calibration, and has also published on mining highly structured data, and has an interest in human-centred AI. He is author of Simply Logical: Intelligent Reasoning by Example and Machine Learning: the Art and Science of Algorithms that Make Sense of Data. His talk "The highs and lows of performance evaluation: Towards a measurement theory for machine learning" will take place take place online on February 8 at 5 pm.
